# Architecture Decision Records (ADR)

## ADR-0001
Clocking

Decision:
All synchronous logic shall use the positive edge of the system clock.

Reason:
Consistency across the entire ForgeAI architecture.

---

## ADR-0002
Reset

Decision:
All synchronous modules shall implement an active-high synchronous reset.

Reason:
Simplifies learning and provides consistent behavior.

---

## ADR-0003
Parameterization

Decision:
Reusable modules shall use parameters where practical.

Reason:
Promotes scalability and reduces duplicated RTL.

## ADR-0004
Architecture Direction

Decision:
ForgeAI shall follow a GPU-inspired parallel compute architecture rather than a TPU-only systolic architecture.

Reason:
A GPU-like architecture provides broader usefulness for matrix math, AI inference, signal processing, simulation, and general parallel workloads. ForgeAI may still include TPU-like MAC arrays internally where useful, but the overall system shall remain flexible and programmable.

## ADR-0005
ForgeCore Execution Model

Decision:
ForgeCore v1 shall execute one instruction at a time using a single-cycle execution model.

Future versions may introduce instruction pipelining after architectural verification.

Reason:
A single-cycle architecture is easier to understand, verify, and debug while establishing the foundation of the instruction set and execution model.

## ADR-0006
Zero Register

Decision:
Register R0 shall be hardwired to zero.

Reads from R0 shall always return 0.

Writes to R0 shall be ignored.

Reason:
A zero register simplifies instruction generation, reduces the need for explicit clear/load-zero operations, and aligns ForgeAI with proven RISC-style architecture patterns.

## ADR-0007
Module Freeze Policy

Once a module passes simulation and satisfies its documented requirements,
its public interface shall be considered frozen.

Future enhancements shall be implemented as new module revisions rather
than modifying verified modules, unless a defect or architectural change
requires otherwise.